<h2>Aging & Cellaring</h2>

<p>The finest Napa Valley wines are built for extended aging, with their aging potential directly tied to quality and structure. Premium Cabernet Sauvignon from estates like Screaming Eagle, Harlan, or Caymus Special Selection can age gracefully for 20-30 years, while exceptional vintages from Inglenook or Stag's Leap Wine Cellars may peak after 15-25 years. Mid-tier Napa Cabernets typically show their best between 5-12 years of age.</p>

<h3 class="text-wine-700">Evolution in the Bottle</h3>

<p>As Napa wines age, their fierce tannins from Cabernet Sauvignon gradually polymerize and soften, while primary blackcurrant and cassis flavors evolve into complex notes of cedar, tobacco, leather, and graphite. The hallmark eucalyptus character from valley floor vineyards mellows into subtle mint undertones. Chardonnays from producers like Kistler or Ramey develop rich honeyed complexity and hazelnut nuances after 8-12 years, replacing their youthful citrus brightness.</p>

<h3 class="text-wine-700">Optimal Storage Conditions</h3>

<p>Store your prized Napa bottles at a consistent <strong>55-58°F</strong> with 60-70% humidity. Position bottles horizontally to keep corks moist, preventing oxidation that would turn your investment into expensive vinegar. Avoid temperature fluctuations above 5°F, which cause damaging cork expansion and contraction.</p>

<h3 class="text-wine-700">Recognizing Perfect Maturity</h3>

<p>Properly aged Napa wines show brick-red edges in the glass, indicating beneficial color evolution rather than browning from heat damage. The nose should display integrated oak with developed tertiary aromas—never sharp alcohol or vegetal green bell pepper notes that suggest premature drinking. <strong>Warning signs of spoilage</strong> include vinegar aromas (acetic acid), wet cardboard smells (TCA cork taint), or flat, lifeless fruit that indicates oxidation. Trust your senses: a well-aged Napa Cabernet rewards patience with unparalleled complexity and silky texture.</p>

